Anonymous Thu 04 Feb 2021 13:36:07 No.36075231 Report
Quoted By: >>36075259 >>36075302 >>36075330
>>36075113
Because It's a very unorthodox point of view which can be used efficiently in some cases, but requires a lot of chiseling and sanding to get right. For these specific stories it's compeltely useless because it's just a relic of greentext, which was never meant to be used as a story medium. So you're gimping yourself from the get go just for an ancillary tradition's sake.
It's
>third
>first
>second
for general purpose. First person stories don't require the additional breaking of the fourth wall that second person implies, and people have a lot more pet peeves about what they would do not being reflected in a second person story than what the character does in a first person story.

tl:dr
if you're gonna go second person keep it short and to a greentext about how you wanna pound a dog girl, If you wanna write a 50 K story switch to third or first.

Anonymous Fri 05 Feb 2021 01:59:04 No.36089897 Report

>>36089088
The artist for that one was Oouna, and if I remember right, it was around $600. Depending on the quality and the complexity of the cover, you should expect to spend anywhere from $300-$1000+, with an extra fee if they charge for copyright transfer (and you should always secure the copyright). I find that different artists of similar skill levels are pretty consistent with their pricing. Keep in mind that you ideally want to make that money back from sales, so budget appropriately for what you expect to sell.
I usually browse FA for good artists and just message them, see if they're interested in work. I sometimes meet people through mutual friends, too.

Anonymous Fri 05 Feb 2021 02:44:01 No.36090806 Report

>>36090132
Networking is good, but the majority of artists that I've worked with I just emailed one day out of the blue. Cultivating a good working relationship with them can be very helpful though, as some artists will let you commission them outside of their usual queue, which is super nice when you're doing time-sensitive stuff.
Honestly, if you have work to offer them and money to pay them what they ask, you can't really go wrong. The worst that can happen is that they politely decline. That's the way you should phrase your job offers, too. Work. Make it clear that this is a commercial project, not you asking them to draw your furry OC getting head from a parrot or something.
Looking at the list of people I've worked with, a lot of them are unfortunately busy or AWOL, but if you want somewhere to start, check out PimpArtist on FA. He's on the cheaper end of the spectrum, and that dude works. Just tell him Snek sent you.
He did this cover for me

Anonymous Fri 05 Feb 2021 05:28:01 No.36094286 Report

>>36093350
Glad to hear you've been enjoying the stories, dude.

In my case, a big chunk of my income comes from Patreon, and the rest I get from commissions and book sales. It's my understanding that my business model isn't typical. Most authors go Amazon exclusive to get into their Kindle program, which means that their books are available as part of a subscription and they get paid per pages read, rather than a lump sum for a book sale. That does require a 90-day exclusivity period, though, which is why I don't do it.
Amazon is all about the algorithm, and that's not something I've cracked yet. People like Cebelius and Tefler do very well there, but when they won't actually tell you how much they're making, it can be hard to determine what the best strategy is. The book I'm writing right now is going to be kind of an Amazon experiment. I want to see what happens when you target a specific demographic super hard, which is something Cebelius advised me to do when I spoke to him.

My business model is pretty much:
>cast a wide net, post free stories everywhere I can
>encourage readers to support me through Patreon or by buying a book if they want more
>use income to commission more book covers so I can sell more books
>repeat

Being able to share my daily updates is super important for me, both because it keeps people engaged, and because it's very motivating. If you just have a finished story you want to sell as a product, I'd recommend going Amazon exclusive.

The most profitable approach would probably be:
>Amazon exclusive for 90 days
>once that period is over, sell on other stores, maybe provide for free on popular sites for advertising purposes
>start a Patreon too because why not, maybe provide things like covers, concept art, and Ebook downloads to supporters

Right now, Tefler is the only author I know of who has somehow mastered both Patreon and Amazon, but I'm not sure how he does it.

Also here's a guide for making Amazon Ebooks.
